data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The temporary compatibility shim you configured in .NET 10 no longer exists.

All four of your synchronous calls will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime:

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

## How to fix

Convert the repository to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key steps:**
1. Return `Task<T>` (or `Task` for void) from every I/O method
2. `await` every EF Core query/save call
3. Propagate `async`/`await` up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.)
4. Remove the now-defunct sync-over-async configuration from your `DbContext` setup

The Cosmos SDK is natively async — this change eliminates the hidden `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` deadlock risk that sync-over-async carried.
